Stopped by @primewood.la today to see
the progress of the new special limited edition Grinch Sketch Series decks with artist @itsandyjenkins.

Six different original sketches by Andy from 1990 are being offered on six different decks, with only 200 of each deck being produced.

Preorder at primewood.la. 

Thank you! 

And a big thank you to @chuck_hults and @swurvana for making such beautiful boards!

With @chrispastras yesterday at @primewood.la.

I’m holding one of the forthcoming Grinch Sketch Series decks and Chris is holding his new ‘Baby Dune’ deck (also being made by Prime).

Seems some folks are a bit confused as to what these new Grinch boards are.

And so here it is: in 1990, artist @itsandyjenkins made a handful of Grinch sketches while working on what would become a board graphic of mine that same year (seen in the bottom left corner of the first pic and in the skate pic here).

Six of those never-before-seen sketches are being printed on decks for a very limited and very special release. Only 200 decks of each sketch are being produced, with all decks to be signed by both me and Andy.

The original Grinch board was one of my favorites—the shape was amazing too—and so it’s really special to be working with Andy again 32 years later and bringing his other Grinch drawings to life.

Final slide here shows the six decks, all of which can be preordered now at primewood.la.

Thank you!

@chuck_hults and @swurvana at @primewood.la are making the Grinch Sketch Series boards all by hand. They’re doing beautiful work!

Skateboarding has lost one of its absolute gems, the legend that we all simply called “O”, skater, photographer, musician, friend, and massive inspiration to so many skaters. He was also one of skating’s funniest. To this day many of us still use some of his inventive and hilarious lingo. He had non-stop energy and made everything FUN. Each and every time we’d go skating we laughed. 

I feel incredibly lucky to have been photographed by O, from my teenage days (second slide) to my very early 20s (the following). 

He encouraged me and never let me give up when I was trying to land a trick he was photographing. He was patient and kind and LOVED skateboarding.

He no doubt made skateboarding better. And I am eternally grateful for his lasting influence in my life.

Thank you, O! 🖤

(first photo of O by another legend, @jgrantbrittain)

Thrilled to announce that my new book
TX | CA 17 is now available to preorder from @stanleybarkerbooks before its release in May. 

The 62 square-format black-and-white pictures in this book were made in the summer of 2017 on a drive from my then adopted home state of Texas to Los Angeles, where I’d lived prior and from where I set out to start photographing from the road in 2006. While I’ve previously published various photographs from this and other similar excursions, TX | CA 17 is the first offering of images selected from a single outing. They are presented in geographical and (rough) chronological order—North Texas, NM, AZ, the California desert, and finally DTLA, where we see the gentleman awaiting his bus.

I’ll be signing copies at @leicauk in May — details to come …

Much of the Texas section in my new book
TX | CA 17 features photos made on or near Highway 287, a favorite road of mine and one that I first explored with cameras back in 2008.

The exposures in the book were made primarily along and surrounding Highways 287, 40/66, 62, and 10, from North Texas to Los Angeles. Many of these places I’ve come to know quite well, with some documented frequently before and since this particular drive. It’s always a pleasure revisiting the familiar—these somehow comforting landmarks; these reminders—and equally exciting to discover new sights, make new pictures, and collect new memories. So you keep going. After sixteen years of photographing outside, I remain fascinated by the American landscape and all its parts both beautiful and curious. 

Copies of the book are shipping now from @stanleybarkerbooks. Thank you!

Throwback to my exhibition at @philbrookmuseum in Tulsa.

Commissioned by Philbrook and on display June 1 through December 2019, the exhibition featured 178 Oklahoma photographs spanning the Meinig and Burnstein galleries in the museum’s satellite location, Philbrook Downtown (now the @bobdylancenter). A selection of Larry Clark’s original Tulsa prints were concurrently presented in the adjacent Smith Gallery.

This particular print grouping is comprised of photographs of various structures from around Oklahoma as seen from my car as I roamed the state in 2018.

Additional OK photographs can be seen via the link in my bio.

And I’m happy to announce that the hardcover exhibition catalog we dreamed up after the exhibition but never got around to producing will finally be released within the next couple of years.

Celebrating Ceren this week for her birthday (August 4) as she is away in her homeland of Türkiye visiting family and working on her @oddbirdcompany. 

She and I visited the Portland area last year for a little getaway and so that I could make photographs for Oddbird. 

Being Turkish, she was thrilled when we stumbled upon this authentic, quaint little neighborhood Turkish restaurant where we enjoyed an incredible meal as she conversed with the friendly proprietor in her native tongue. Then, an evening stroll on which I would make more pictures of her with one of the little pocket cameras I’d brought with us. 

I love the light here, the film grain and the warmth, and the off-placed photo of Atatürk. 

And the sense of optimism, of hope on Ceren’s face in the second photo. Such an incredible softness to her. I’m never not moved when photographing her, even when it’s just snapshots like these. 

#35mm #nikon28ti

Celebrating Ceren this week for her birthday (August 4).

Here she is in April 2019 with our three daughters shortly after the birth of the youngest, Edith. It was nice just sitting there, watching them celebrate as I quietly made pictures. 

The bond that these four ladies have is truly special. And just how incredibly well Ceren balances motherhood and being a wife, artist and business owner never ceases to inspire. And for always making herself available to assist me in my own creative efforts, despite her busyness, forever there with incredible patience and insight, I owe so much to her.

Roadside note-taking, 2017

This was during a drive I took with @raymond.molinar from Texas to Los Angeles in the summer of 2017 to make new photographs along what have become some very familiar western routes. A handful of the square-format black-and-white photos that I made on this trip can be seen in my latest book, TX | CA 17, now available from @stanleybarkerbooks.

HWY 287 in North Texas shortly after we’d departed. Behind me in the first slide you can see the truck with the American flag and hand-painted watermelon signs on it that I photographed as seen in the second slide.

This is my first book to feature images from a single outing—they are presented in geographical and (rough) chronological order, moving east to west. 

For those who’ve not yet gotten a copy, visit
Stanley/Barker’s website via the link in their bio.

(first photo by Ray on #35mm film)

Recently uncovered some behind-the-scenes pictures from my first-ever photo outings in 2006-7 that I hadn’t seen in quite a long time. 

A pic here during the making of an 8x10 Polaroid of the left-behind Exxon sign near Santa Margarita, California (swipe).

The camera, which I still own and occasionally use, is a beautiful old 1930s Century Universal 8x10 that I’d acquired shortly after discovering that Polaroid made large format films. An incredibly fun and very pivotal time for me photographically.

Happy 2024 to all!

Hope everyone had a good 2023 …

Thrilled @raymond.molinar and I were able to finally open @eaglerockcamera in December after working on its setup all year. Thanks to all those who’ve paid us a visit in the few weeks we’ve been up and running. An incredible experience thus far. 

And to have collaborated again with the lovely @stanleybarkerbooks on my book TX | CA 17, which came out in May. 

With that, S/B will also be releasing the book’s follow-up, TX | CA 19, in May of the new year (first set of slides).

No set dates yet, but the books to follow over the coming years will be OK, the hardcover catalog companion to my 2019 exhibition of Oklahoma photographs at @philbrookmuseum in Tulsa (second set of slides), MARQUIS, a collection of black-and-white and color photographs made on a 2022 drive from Florida to Los Angeles in my 1987 Mercury Grand Marquis (third set of slides), the second printing of my 2018 book A PLAIN VIEW (fourth set of slides), and MORNING WALKS, a collection of color photographs made while on morning walks around Los Feliz, Los Angeles, in early 2022 (final set of slides).

More to come …

As always, I greatly appreciate the continued support …

Thank you!
